ce:section.ce:para:
Molecular orbital distributions and energy gap values were calculated to study the effect of N doping and IL modification on the activity of CDs (
                        Fig. 10). The molecular frontier orbital theory indicates that the highest occupied molecular orbital energy (E

                           HOMO
                        ) and the lowest unoccupied molecular orbital energy (E

                           LUMO
                        ) determine the chemical reaction activity of a molecule, and the energy gap of them (ΔE = E

                           LUMO

                        -E

                           HOMO
                        ) reflects the reactivity of the molecule to a certain extent. The HOMO and LUMO orbitals of CD are mainly distributed on benzene rings. After N doping, HOMO and LUMO orbitals are distributed on pyridine-like N and graphitic-like N. However, a small amount of N doping cannot reduce the ΔE value of CD. After ionic liquid modification, the HOMO orbitals of IL-CD (N) are mainly concentrated on the heterocycle where N is located, and the LUMO orbitals are more uniformly distributed on the CDs. Although there is no distribution of HOMO and LUMO orbitals on the ionic liquid, the ΔE can be greatly reduced, and make the HOMO of IL-CD and IL-CD (N) closer to the Fermi level of Fe (−5.177 eV) [46]. This is one of the reasons why the inhibitor films formed by IL-CD and IL-CD (N) are stronger.
